text: This beer is in my top 5. Its amazing. Its refreshing, tasteful, and everything a beer should hope to be. Its impossible to find but worth the quest.

Draft at The Pour House in Westmont, NJ. 

Pours a dark chestnut brown color thats completely opaque with purplish/plum hues and a one finger beige head that slowly settles into a thin ring. Sporadic splotches of lace left behind.

Surprisingly roasty aroma forthe style with a bit of toast, dark chocolate, caramel and coffee bean. This is not overwhelming, however, with subtle earthy hops and a good bit of estery dark fruit notes, notably grape and dark cherry. 

Medium bodied and again, has a bit more roast than expected. The experimental ingredients give complexity to a style that can become boring adding a nice balance to the alcohol sweetness and estery dark fruit flavors. Hints of dark chocolate, toffee, oatmeal and subtle coffee bean flavor followed by alcohol, plum, raisin and dark cherry. Kind of like a roasted dark chocolate covered cherry. Theres also some subtle hop bitterness and well masked ABV making this complex beer very easy to drink. Nice experimental beer from dfh for a change.
This pilsner is so interesting with bits of chocolate and candy. You can grab the hint of coffee and this taste is a treat in the fall.

Bottle @ ZZTX. Dark amber color.
Nutty, caramelly aroma with a hint of roast. Malty sweet flavor, caramelly and nutty. Some dried figs.

Bottle @ ZZT X, small sample, thanks all for sharing! Slight hazy light brown color, short head. Aroma of spicy yeast, bit caramel and chocolate, bit earthy hop. Quite bitter for an abbey dubbel, slight sweet, malty. USA take on an abbey dubbel.

Bottle @ ZZT X shared by MrHangover. Lightly unclear red brown color with a dark red glare coming through. Smell and taste sweetish, lightly malts, raisins, mint. Decent body and carbonation. Hmm not a lot to tell about this one. Its ok Id say.
Bottle @ ZZTX. Aroma is light s. Oke, red fruits, herbal notes. Flavour is red fruits, some malt. LRAB.
Bottle @zzt10 shared by MrHangover. Brown color with a off-white head. Smells and tastes sweet, dark fruit, mint.

Bottle @ ZZT X, courtesy of me. Pours a clear reddish brown beer with a quickly disappearing off white head on top. Aroma of chocolate, toffee, malts and caramel. Flavor has a light sweet touch to it, light caramel and has this flat mouthfeel. There is a big chocolate and nutty presence in this beer. Interesting stuff here.. I like it.
Bottle @ ZZT 10 shared by MrHangover. Dark amber to brown colour with a small off-white head. Smells raisins, sweet. Tastes sweet, raisins, herbs, meh. Medium body, soft carbo.

Bottle shared at ZZT 10 thanks to Mrhangover. Pours hazy reddish brown with a small off white head. Aroma of raisins, overripe dark fruit, caramel, red fruits. Flavour is moderate sweet, light bitter and a touch of acid. Medium bodied with light carbonation.

"DFHs description says dubbel, but this seems more like a belgianesque porter to me. Pretty nice brew. Belgian yeasty spice is there, but subtle...some fruitiness, and lots of dry roast. Finishes dry too. Feel is nice. Gladly, the honey is slight as well and not overdone. Nice job!"

Dark brown with rimming beige head ; aroma slightly malty and roasty ; Flava is sweetish upfront hints of cherry or plum; then fades into a notice mildly roasty grainy profile ; feels medium some fizz; finishes dry slightly sticky sweetness and grainy roastiness

Transfer from BA review from 6-26-12 - 
Served in a 10 oz chalice glass

Appearance  Served a deep brown color with a billowy light tan head. The head had a moderate amount of lacing and gave way to a medium amount of lacing.

Smell  The aroma was quite roasty. Roasted malt with nice hints of espresso and chocolate. A lighter sweetness comes to the nose as well; lightly molasses in nature with good hints of burnt sugar.

Taste  The taste started out much sweeter then I initially expected from the nose. The brew started with a great sweet flavor of brown sugar and molasses complimenting the very roasty malt flavor. The roasted malt becomes more brown bread as the taste advances, with some light notes of carob and chocolate coming to the tongue. At the end the taste some Belgian spicy flavors enter the scene and overall leave a rather roasty and burnt sugar and spice flavor on the tongue.

Mouthfeel  The body of the brew is normal. A thicker body would have been better for the roasty flavor of the brew. The carbonation level is on the just below average side and is very suiting; allowing all the roasty flavors to sit on the tongue and be sensed.

Overall  A very nice darker brew with interesting taste combinations and transitions. Well worth a try if you have the chance.

From 750 bottle to tulip glass. Aromas of strong chocolate and moderate floral hops. Pours a slightly hazy cola with clear garnet around the edges. Head is taupe and starts massive, but fades quickly. Complex flavor of bittersweet cocoa, solid yeast assertiveness, earth and floral highlights.

2012 bottle to pint glass
I was saving this for some reason, but no longer care. Is a dubbel going to age well? I guess were all about to find out.
Dark fruits, milk chocolate, grains, nutmeg, and cherry. The colour is a deep reddish brown with a very creamy off white head. The taste is roasted malt, cherry, nutmeg, oak, brown sugar and honey and rooibos. This is a good dubbel and looking back through a bunch of other ratings, it appears that this ages well with perhaps the cherry being more prevalent than early on. Im not sure because this just may be my palate.

750 ml. bottle. Pours a red with a little brown with a tan head. Aromas of fruit, chocolate and coffee. Very sweet flavors with brown sugar and light fruit. Not a hoppy beer, more comparable to a wine in my opinion. Sweet and smells of fruit.

750ml bottle in a tulip. Pours very dark brown with a lacy, beige head. Aroma of dark malts, some chocolate and coffee and nuttiness and floral notes and spices, plus some light bitterness. Flavor has a lot going on and I am not really familiar with all of these ingredients so I dont know whats what. Average texture. A really interesting beer with a lot going on and its pretty tasty with the alcohol well hidden.

9/15/2012. 750 ml. bottle. Pours red-brown with a tan head. Aromas of dark malt, dried fruit, chocolate and coffee. Sweet, sticky flavors with brown sugar and light fruit. Light on hops, but very good balance and complexity.

750ml bottle. Pours a dark ruby, reddish brown color with a two finger light tan fluffy head that lasts and leaves good lacing. The aroma has a floral, herbal characteristic mixing with some chocolate, honey and roasted malts. Taste is caramel and brown sugar up front, nutty, woody, hints of cocoa, toasted grains and roasted dark malts, a light tea-like essence from mid-palate on, with light spices and earthy hops for a relatively dry finish. Medium body and carbonation with a good creamy finish.
Bottle. Pour is a dark amber with white head. Chocolate, dark fruits and really sweet. Solid beer but a full bottle would be too much.

Dark brown pour some tan head. Was super fizzy coming out of the bottle. Aroma of tomato rooibus, roasted nuts, honey, cola. Taste is strongly of rooibus with woody notes some tobacco flavors. Fades into nuts then honey sweet finish. Light-medium watery body with light carb and moderate to strong acidity to help balance. Alcohol is well hidden. Not as sickly sweet as other dubbels = great!

Bottle. Colour...nearly black with a thick white head. Nose...coffee like, herbaceous and savoury spice. Palate...delicate CO2, semi sweet, with flavours of Postum, chicory root, and cola. Theres a distinct but o booze at the back of the palate and a nutty flavour that leans towards filberts. Not sure this is an abbey dubbel, but nice nonetheless.

On tap at BW, light brown, thick creamy head. Unusual aroma, almost coffee like. Taste is a little smokey. Interesting to try, but that is it.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a nice deep red, brown from a distance with some eggshell fizz on the rim. The aroma is great, rich roasted grains, chicory, some Belgian fruits. The flavor is rich and very big. Lots of crazy things going on, sport of a mild Belgian dark porter, with hearty roasted notes, some robust chocolate and dried fruits. At first I could taste the rooibos but it quickly blends nicely into one complete roasted thing. Not much on the Belgian front but the intricacies of it set it apart from American imperial browns and porters and it is totally different that a Belgian mild stout or dubbel. Very good, I would not call it a dubbel, more a blend of an American strong brown ale mixed with a Belgian dark strong ale.
Dark brown and off white head. Aroma is msty and coppery. Taste is sweet and funk. Palate is a little watery, but finishes a little sticky.
Hazy reddish brown. Aroma is toasted grain, toffee, honey, fig, mysterious spices. Sweet on the palate, herbal finish. Taste is tea, nutmeg, honey, chocolate, mysterious spices. Unique and tasty.
Bottle share. Deep brown. Aroma of chocolate, oak, raisin. Taste is woody, dark chocolate, caramel, spices. Complex.

Appearance:
A beautiful brushed tan head covers liquid depths that speak of worn mahogany and cherry woods.

Nose:
Bark, sage, figs, exotic mushrooms. Raw peppercorns in the back. Western saddles and broken in leather. Essence of farm dust and grazing livestock  massive musk without the poop. Taro root. Dried figs, juniper, and black root. Star anise.

Palate:
Out of nowhere I am left with tart apples that pucker the cheeks and tickle the tastebuds. The Wild West meets old Europe meets the herbalist meets the rainforest in a crazy mélange of flavors that tastes of time itself. Very rustic and musky in the back with endless forests of bark, trees, and fallen foliage. Dry brittle parching bakers chocolate along the edges. Rich spicy earthy peppery Bordeaux and Zinfandel grapes in the middle. A gin-ish essence pervades the palate with star anise while wild mushrooms grow underneath. Caraway seeds. Old red wine soaked leather sacks. A mysterious mixture of green herbs in the middle. Touch of old black earth in the back. Very parching.

Final Thoughts:
A perplexing thought-provoking beer from the folks at Dogfish Head that leaves me still wondering if I liked the beer or I like the experience. Maybe Ill have to find another bottle to decide. Either way, if Mother Nature and Father Time had a baby, its name would be URKontinent.

(An original written work by Beer Ambassador, LLC. Plagiarism is not tolerated)
On tap @ Pizza Inferno in SF. Some interesting flavors in this one. Dark, malty, sweet and a little earthy. Good abbey dubbel.
Dark amber colour with a white head. Sweet aroma. Powerful dark malt flavour with hints of red and black licorice. Smooth with some carbination on the tongue.

Bottle from Wegmans Leesburg. Pours brown with a thin khaki head. Nice aromatics on the nose. Definitely malt on the tongue but also other awesome herbs and spices mixed in. This stuff is fucking fantastic.

Refrigerated 75 cl brown bottle poured into a tulip.  Pours dark brown with big light brown head.  Aroma is sweet and roasty.  Taste is chocolate, dark belgian sugar, some earthy, some coffee, hint of honey,  and hazelnut.  Really complex and not that hard to drink.  Good dubbel that is also part chocolate stout and part nut brown ale.  Becomes more dubbel  as it warms and less nut brown ale & chocolate stout.

Bottled 750.  Nose is sweet with plenty of rich roast and underlying chocolate, theres some frozen syrup / candi / molasses for complexity, mild plums, roasted seeds.  A really vibrant earthy/grainy feel!  Even some sweet malted milk balls.  Noisy pour, deepest dark ruby with a frothing tan head.  In the mouth, malted milk toward the front and various roastings pushed way to the back, lots more cherry and red berry, light black currants and mineral strokes.  Faintest of herbal qualities, somewhat indistinct; very low bitterness and medium sweetness.  Medium body yields gentle slow warming and a gorgeous velvety malty feel.  I love reading off the special ingredients used, as theyre among my favorite occasionals in the kitchen; here they go utterly unnoticed in the mouth (though may contribute to some of the roasty aromatics) and prove the gimmick unnecessary -- this is nothing more than a really good dubbel!

Dark brown pour with creamy tan head and lace. Aroma is brown sugar and rock candi. Flavor is sweet brown sugar on the front. Sweet chocolate and a hinto coffee. Light medium bitter finish. Lingering after taste of sweet maltiness.

A very dark-ruby red with a off-white head. The nose is strong with wild sugars and floral notes. The taste is very complex and multi-layered. The candied sugar is difficult to relate to other things.  Again Dogfish has struck me with awe and I love it.

Appearance:  very dark brown with reddish highlights, a half-finger of tan head, and minimal lacing.   Aroma: smells like a dubbel mixed with a roasty coffee stout.   Taste: tastes like a belgian dark strong ale with stout-like roast and the herbal character of an old ale or gruit.   Finish: lingering dubbel sweetness with a bit of herbal astringency.  Notes: Very interesting concept and a solid, but not exceptional execution.  Glad I tried it, and I continue to appreciate DFHs use of interesting ingredients.
Fairly well made dubbel here.  Dont know whats so ancient unique or crazy about this.  Its just your ol run of the mill dubbel with no real flaws.  Nutty, spicy and chocolatey.

Interesting looking.  Pours hazy copper/brownish hue, reddish and ruby on edges.  Looks... inviting? Enticing?  Looks GOOD.  Smells vaguely honey-ish.  Tastes GREAT.  Lots of interesting flavors that my blunt palate is floored and confused by.  Sweet finish.  Must... buy... more!

750ml bottle. Pours a dark brown with small tan head. Aroma of dark fruit, Belgian yeast, chocolate, roasted malt, and earthyness.  Taste is roasted malt, chocolate, Belgian yeast, some cherry notes, spice, and some nutty flavors.
Again like any if these big dogfish head beer none of the advertised flavors are there. Great standard double, like it a lot

Uploading old ratings that were missing comments. Lots of sweet malt and tropical fruit. A little jumbled. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Aroma is becks dark but toastier, taste is toasted nutty Belgian becks dark with a touch of cherry, and a floral whiff, finishes tootsie roll laced with cherry caramel notes. if you remember Petes wicked ale from early mid nineties, theres some notion of that sans hops.

Edit: I really criticize dogfish head BC or price. Burton baton and 90 are phenomenal. I like the idea for a lot of DF beers, but I like beer more. Their beers are delicious, their ideas are genious, the two dont always meet up. This time they kinda did too well. Wish this wasnt so balanced.can also be described as a session ale you cant session, and an exotically flavored ale with too many overtones of simplicity. 

"Smuttynose brown dog ale on acid"

750mL bottle, bottled in 2012B, opened on the last night in my 1st house. Pours dark red, orange, and brown; small foamy beige head. Aromas of esters upfront, with banana and clove. Oats and roasty malt are present, with molasses, honey, clover, raisin, and some burnt toffee and coffee. Cocoa, chocolate, and nuts in the periphery. The flavor is cocoa and gourd first, with, spices and chocolate; this moves to cocoa and fudge, honey and vanilla, and a lingering cocoa finish, with an espresso aftertaste. Low/medium carbonation, slightly warming. Really nice; earthy and rustic. [1138]
Draft at crunchy's. Dark copper with a small head. Tons of competing aromas and flavors of honey and dark fruits and sugars. I was left thinking I liked it.

3rd June 2012Very dark brown beer, reddish. Good pale tan head. Nose of nuts and spicy unsweet bubblegum. Smooth, semi dry palate. Mild fine carbonation. Smooth dry malt, soft. A minty coolness. Mild and subtle red berry fruits. Spicy bubblegum and banana ester. Subtle nuts. A fairly dry finish. Unusual complex beer, tasty.

On tap at the brew pub in Rehoboth Beach, served in a tasting glass. Pours hazy chestnut with a minimal tan froth and no proper head. On the nose are roasted malts with molasses, herbs and hints of coffee and perhaps chocolate. The flavour is moderately sweet throughout, with roasty notes from the nose. It evolves with complex earthy, herby and spicy notes and closes with a long, complex herby-hoppy finish. On the palate, it is medium in body with a creamy texture and soft carbonation. Overall, this is a nice, complex dark Belgian-style ale. A complex brew that puts diverse ingredients to good use. 2012-06-08

A - pours dark mahogany. Low very quickly dissipating. S - grains, honey and dark fruits on the nose. Some brown sugar, molasses and mustiness in the middle.  Vegetal and coffee ground notes on the end as well. M - high carb, a little lighter than expected. Lingering sweeter finish. Light Medium body. T - grains and dark fruits once again make an appearance in the front.  Smoke, cola (Dr. Pepper when cooler), mineral water, molasses, brown sugar, faint prunes and fruit flavored tea. Coffee grounds on the end.  Basically many shades and flavors of brown.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
750ml bottle pours dark amber with large tan head. Coffee and chocolate cherry aroma. Cherry and chocolate taste up front with a bit of honey and coffee following. A real mash up of flavors.

Bouteille de 750 ml partagée lors dune dégustation Ratebeer Montréal. Arôme: Légère odeur de caramel avec une pointe fruitée. Apparence: La couleur est brune. Présence dun mince col mousseux et dune fine dentelle sur le verre. Saveur: Léger goût de caramel avec une pointe de chocolat et de fruité. Durée moyenne de larrière goût. Palette: Le corps est moyen avec une texture légèrement huileuse. Moyenne effervescence en bouche. (Rating #4604)

This beer had tons of flavors going on. Aromas of cherry, honey, sweet fruits, raisin, chocolate, and light roast. Poured pretty dark with an off-white head. Flavor was intense, with a good dose of honey, sweet fruits, candied fruits, chocolate, cherries, prunes, figs, nuts, and roast. Crazy complex but almost overpowering in my opinion. Very good though.

750ml Bottle
Appearance - Dark brown, frothy head
Aroma - Tootsie rolls, raspberries, rose petals, honey
Taste - Cocoa, cherries, honey, brown sugar, bread

What a complex beer this was, thanks for sharing, OmegaX! This was a rich beer that changed dramatically as it warmed up. Very good stuff here!
750ml->SA. Dark amber brown with frothy offwhite head.  Aroma: chocolate, dark fruit, malt and caramel.  Taste: sweet, dark fruit fruit, spices, with earth notes.  Good, complex.

Poured from a 750 ml bottle. Pours a darker brown with a beige head of foam. Not much retention. Aroma is nutty and sweet malt. Some cocoa comes through nicely. Taste is mildly sweet. Decent mouthfeel.

Bottle from who knows where? Nice dark fruit notes, roobios, and honey. All of Sam's beers are supremely unique. Nice beer to complete some major offerings near the end of the night. Nice beer. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

750 ml bottle into chalice, bottled code 2012B.  Pours crystal clear extremely dark reddish brown color with a 1-2 finger fairly dense light khaki head with nice retention, that reduces to a thin cap that lingers.  Light spotty foamy lacing on the glass, with a fair amount of streaming carbonation.  Aromas of big chocolate, raisin, prune, toast, coffee, roasted malt, pepper, clove, honey, caramel, toffee, floral, dark bread, herbal, and earthy yeast spiciness.  Damn nice aromas with great balance and complexity of malt, spices, and yeast esters.  Taste of chocolate, raisin, fig, caramel, toast, toffee, roasted malt, honey, coffee, clove, dark bread, candi sugar, floral, herbal, and earthy yeast spiciness.  Lingering notes of chocolate, dark fruits, caramel, toast, toffee, roasted malt, coffee, honey, candi sugar, herbal, floral, and earth on the finish for a good bit.  Fantastic flavor balance and complexity; all herbs and spices compliment the Dubbel style nicely; with zero cloying flavors present after the finish.  Medium carbonation and medium-full bodied; with a creamy and fairly slick mouthfeel that is nice.  Alcohol is extremely well hidden with nearly zero warming noticed after the finish.  Overall this is a highly excellent spiced Dubbel style!  Great flavor complexity and balance with the complimenting spices; and extremely smooth to sip on.  This was a highly enjoyable offering.
Bottle. Dark red pour, white head. Aroma, of toast, cherries, light tea notes. Taste is fruity, good caramel flavors, pepper, really special taste and aroma. Palate is well carbed, medium body.

750ml bottle: Pours a barely transparent dark mahogany with a stringy lacing froth of off-white head. Has a lightly sweet toasted dark caramel malty nose with a touch of cherries, chocolate and coriander. Starts with pretty good fullness and well-dissolved carbonation with some lightly sweet doughy dark malts with a touch of earthy dark fruits and dark chocolate before a drier roasty bittersweet finish. A pretty unique brew and managed to meld some interesting flavors.
Pours deep reddish brown with a very thin khaki head.  aroma is chocolate, roast coffee beans and toast.  Taste is sweet with some light roasty bitters.  Medium bodied and very smooth.  Very nice.

Bottle from Total Wine, Naples. The pours deep brown with a small head. The nose is chocolate, robust rye bread, caramel, rustic earth, some toasted nuts. The taste is strong licorice, rye bread, toasted grain, chocolate, caramel. Full bodied, rich. Very interesting. Overall, pretty tasty stuff.
1 pt 9.4 oz brown bottle with raised shark. Medium body. Nice slight candi sugar flavor melds well with  slightly dry maltiness. Smooth.

750mL bottle, pours a very deep dark mahogany with a small beige head. Aroma of spices upfront which are very foreign to me, dark fruits, and candied sugar. Flavour of various complimentary spices, quite rich and complex, a vague hint of dark fruit and more spices. Very spicy, but in a cohesive way without any harsh edges. Doesnt come across as a dubbel, but an experimental spiced beer.

Bottle. Pours a deep dark brown with a small tan head that left nice lacing. Aroma of chocolate, dark fruit, roasted malts, caramel and some nuttiness. Flavor was slightly sweet with dark fruit, caramel, honey, cocoa/chocolate, roasted malts and coffee.

Tap at Hops and Pie.  Clear dark ruby brown under a light beige head. Nose was full of dark sweetness, with some boozy raisin, grainy toffee, and some sort of earthy wood. Great complexities of chocolate, earthy toffee, light figs, a little oak, a little sugar cane...earthy and complex but plenty sweet.

Wasnt sure what this was when I drank it, still not sure. Its nice though. Pours dark brown, almost black with an offwhite head. Roast malt, fruit, oak, fruit, cherry and some dark fruit in the aroma. Flavour has all these notes plus some herbs and spices, yeasty berry sourness and nuts. Quite dry, smooth, not overly heavy yet quite creamy in the mouth. Long roasty finish with another twist of sourness. Notes of port and alcohol. Interesting.

Bottle at home shared with my dad. Appearance is deep brown with a one-finger khaki head and great lacing. Sesame seeds, light honey, a touch of roast, marshmallows, notes of cherry, and red licorice in the aroma. Very reminiscent of a brown ale. Taste is graham crackers, honeycomb, malty, light vanilla, wood, and cocoa with a touch of spice on the backend. Creamy mouthfeel with soft carbonation. Pretty interesting beer, much like a honey, brown ale.

On tap @ the Brewpub-Dark brown pour w/a moderate tan head. Fruity aroma. Medium creamy body, flavors of sweet malt, caramel/toffee, & dark fruit/cherries, and some licorice. Had a good bit of carbonation. Reminded me a little bit of their chicory stout, but a little sweeter, not as stoutlike.

Bottle. Pours a dark amber color with a small off-whit ehead. Has a fruity malty spicy caramel aroma. Fruity malty spicy caramle and weak chocolae flavor. Has a fruity malty spicy caramel and chocolate finish.

Pours a two finger khaki head that fades slowly leaving a good lace.  Deep mahogany/brown color.  Good carbonation and medium bodied.  Baked chocolate nose and flavor is semisweet chocolate/coffee and Belgian yeast. Higher ABV is totally hidden. Another decent offering from DFH. Pricey at $14.00 for a 750ml (not a 22oz) bottle from Tullys Beer and Wine Wells, ME.
Very smooth. Looks good. Drinks better. dogfish head has another winner in its stable.

My Bottom Line:
Raspberry fruitiness, chicory-like roast and sugary cereals create a puzzling but pleasant profile for this, yet another strange DFH brew whose sole purpose appears to be strangeness and not the accomplishment of a particular flavor profile, texture, flavor sequence, etc.

Further Personal Perceptions:
-A veil of foam covers the misty brown.
-Carbonation is soft, making the brew feel heavier than it is in this case.
-Earthiness is tasted throughout as well.
-Im getting tired of all these DFH brews with exotic ingredient lists which end up being showcased in a similarly plump, sugary mouthfeel.

Bottle.

Dark brown/cider color; Medium creamy body; Aroma of toasted sweet malt, caramel/toffee, & dark fruit; Flavor of sweet malt, caramel/syrup, honey; dark fruit, chocolate, and some licorice; Nicely balanced; Overall, a bit sweet - but pretty decent.

Bottle thanks to Veldrid: Poured dark brown with red edges, head was creamy off white to tan. You could hear bubbling from the carbonation. Aroma is dark fruits, roasted malts, sweet honey and chocolate. Taste has a light chocolate bitterness up front that subsides to dark fruit and blends to a coffee bean/roasted malt back. The finish is dry and yet still complex on the tongue.

From notes: Poured hazy nut brown with a 3-finger tan head.  Earthy aroma with a sweet, nutty note and touches of yeast and spice beneath.  Medium body with a slight syrupy thickness.  Sweet flavor with earthy spice notes and a touch of honey at the back.  A mild citrusy note appears as it warms.

750ml Bottle. The pour was a muddy dark brown with a slight cranberry red hue and a small (1 finger or less) tan creamy head that was mostly diminishing, down to a thin film with a small collar and good sheeting of lacing that coated the glass.

The aroma was all about the chocolate with a roasted grain malt and a sweet doughy yeast with a note of dark fruit (cherries and currant), a hint of roasted coffee and a mild nuttiness.

The taste was extremely malty and a tad sweet with a big note of chocolate and a touch of coffee throughout with the finish being quite fruity and having a mild nutty alcohol ending. The flavor stuck around for an average time after the swallow with a bold roasty mocha flavor left to linger on the taste buds.

Mouthfeel was medium in body and creamy in texture with a nice soft carbonation.

Overall a smooth, creamy and rather tasty brew that had a wonderful mocha, berry, coffee flavor, a mild alcohol warming and an awesome drinkability. All these components combined, make this beer sensationally delicious...

pours a clear dark mahogany with a small tan head, and good lacing.

smell is of cocoa, earth, some spice, and malt.

taste is thick, cocoa, some spice, malt, bourbon barrel, and few hops.  ends smooth and a little bitter.

750 ml bottle.  Pours brown in color with some reddish tints when held to the light.  Small off white head.  The aroma is herbal and lightly fruity, earthy, cocoa, cherry, and roasted malt.  Lots of different things going on in the nose which is pretty good.  The flavor has much of the same while adding some belgian candi sugar and a splash of alcohol.  The flavor is a bit busy for me.  Nice to try once, especially since I didnt buy it.

Bottle, 
this ale had a dark brown pour that is a dark red / ruby when placed in front of a lamp, this beer was opaque but I could see through it a little at the sides of he glass, the pour made an initial one and half finger light tan colored head that receded to a thin cover with a couple of open spaces, this drink left some spots and small fingers of lacing that rolled off the glass a bit, there was no sediment on the bottom of the bottle, 

the aromas were earthy dry chocolate, faint Rootbeer, toasted malt and some roasted malt notes that resembled a brown ale, dark roasted grains, faint toasted bread, prune and date dark fruit, malt, molasses and brown sugar sweetness, petite floral notes, a little muted herb and spice that I could not place except there appeared to be just a little green cardamom in the mix, licorice in the background to, 

it had flavors of toasted and roasted malt, a little chocolate, caramel, prune and date fruit, alcohol esters, 
some earthy malt like flavor, the finish had some drying on the tongue but there still was some malt and sweetness skimming by, there was a little pepper, 

the mouth feel was a little less than medium with a nice creamy feel on the palate, and average carbonation, 

the first sniff reminded me of an Imperial Stout, big malt nose with a little chocolate and other things, the nose was nice but it did not come across as a Belgian Dubbel, I did not smell the alcohol but it was noticeable on the tongue when tasted, it was not hot or flashy alcohol but I knew it was there, and this did not take away from the enjoyment of this drink, but I was surprised to notice 8% alc. in a beer, this beer was nice but I do not know if I would buy this again.
Pours a dark brown with a thin tan head. Aroma of roasted malt, chocolate, nuts. Taste is of chocolate, honey, yeast, spice, and tea. Smooth, medium body. Impressive.

On tap.  Dark brown, not quite opaque, with a thin tan head.  Aroma is sweet and malty.  Flavor is pleasant, with some almost stout-like coffee and chocolate characteristics, which are more prominent than the moderately sweet malts and sugars.  Lacks the cloying sweetness occasionally found in the dubbel style.  The flavors come together very well, with nothing overpowering, but plenty of nuanced chocolate, candy, mild fruit, light bitterness, and slight dryness in the finish.
Chocolate malts up front, with a slight coffee backbone. Another win for the boys at DFH.

So hit and miss...and lately a ton of misses.  Still I continue to purchase every new beer I see from them.  What can I say, Im a ticker!  Murky chestnut brew with a small khaki head.  Dough, caramel, nuttiness, cocoa, roasted malt.  Unfortunately, the flavor is less than the sum of its parts.  Lets stay on this continent, use more traditional ingredients, and get back to basics (cant believe that a guy with a motto of "go big or go home" is saying this).  Being unique and different is awesome, if its not intentional.

Decent beer, but seems to be co fused about its identity between a Dubbel and a Belgian Strong Dark Ale. A slight booziness with mild fruit overshadowed by some earthy tones. Some serious chocolate. Really starts to get better as it warms up. Overall solid, but not something I would seek out.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from Total Wine. Pours a dark brown with a slim tan head that diminishes quickly to froth. The aroma is simultaneously sweet & roasty. Flavors of toast, subtle soy sauce, almond, biscuit, coffee bean. High carbonation and medium/full body. This brew is like a cross between a dubbel and a stout. Another good experiment from DFH.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Good beer. Interesting flavor. Not sure I can identify the individual components if the ingredients. But overall enjoyable. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Dark color, roast smell.  Smooth malt taste, nice clean finish.  excellent beer.

An interesting beer, fresh from Premiere Gourmet. Pours dark, above average mouthfeel, good drinkability. A sipper, great after the fish. Flavours: Chocolate, chicory roast, lots of hops, a little yeast, honey finish.

Bottle. Pours a cloudy brown with a medium creamy beige head that lasts awhile leaving spotty lacing along the glass. The aroma is cocoa nibs, figs, and licorice. Medium mouthfeel with a strong coffee and chocolate with dark fruits and nice smooth finish. Hides alcohol well, a very good specialty grain from Dogfish Head.

On tap @ Lazy Boy Saloon.  Poured a dark brown head with reddish hues, thin tan head, and excellent lacing.  Aroma is roasted malt, nuts, and genmai-cha roasted tea.  Taste begins with bready malt flavor followed by dark fruit and a hint of bakers chocolate.  Enjoyable sticky mouthfeel with flavors lingering.

750 ml bottle into a DFH signature glass. 2012A. 

A - Pours a dark brown body. Lets some light through with a red tinge. One finger light tan head. Settles into a small cap with thick edging. Solid lacing and retention.

S - Im not familiar with ANY of these ingredients. So I guess the notes Im picking up are somewhat novice and pedestrian...large roasty notes. Im picking up hazelnut, bittersweet chocolate, sweetened coffee, caramel, and some dark fruits. Earthy and grainy finish. 

T - Same as the nose. Roasty with hazelnut, bread, dark fruits, coffee, caramel, and an earthy and slightly bitter finish. Taste is somewhat dubbel like, but with a really peculiar twist. Each ingredient is faint and subtle, but there is a lot of ingredients vying for attention and it doesnt meld together very gracefully. Alcohol becomes present as it warms up. The weakest link is the mouth feel, somewhat thin and lacking in body. Carbonation also seems a bit low.

O - Another unique and interesting beer. It is enjoyable though.

Drank on tap in Maine.  Deep brown pour; thin head; spare lacing; soft, creamy; very rich, nice chocolate flavor.  Great in small doses

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle: Poured a deep hazy brown color ale with a large foamy head with good retention and some lacing. Aroma consists of sweet Belgian style malt base with clear note of Roobios tea. Taste is a solid mix between some sweet Belgian malt with residual candi sugar notes with some good notes of Roobios tea. Body is quite full with good carbonation and no apparent alcohol. Most of the spices used in this recipe are kind hard to distinguish though the Roobios is very nice and more pronounced. Belgian malt backbone is very solid and overall I quite enjoyed this beer.

major complexity, this is not a beer that can drink without noticing the amazing flavors that are everywhere. looks like cola has flavors of chocolate, berries, fig and spices. the mouth feel is slight thinnish but its nice and smooth. this is the winner.
The aroma is very toasted with coffee, chocolate, roasted grains, and fruit. The appearance is like cola. The taste is like the aroma. the palate is a bit thin. Overall a great beer.

THOUGHTS: A very complex dubbel. One of the creamiest beers Ive ever had.
TECHNICAL: Bottle. Poured a very dark reddish brown that was nearly brown in the glass with bright red highlights and an average, off-white head that mostly diminished and left good lacing. The aroma had moderate to heavy roasted and milk chocolate malts; moderate to heavy spicy yeast; cherry; other dark fruit; something floral; tobacco; something earthy; something herbal; herbal tea; and hints of vanilla, pepper licorice and cola. The initial flavor was light to moderately sweet and lightly bitter; while the finish was moderately sweet and slightly bitter. There was chocolate, roasted malt, a little coffee, cherry, other dark fruit, honey, something herbal, something earthy, tea, herbal tea, more honey, a little vanilla, maybe some licorice, spicy yeast, and something floral.

Pouring at Belgian Beer Fest.  Pours a clear deep brown with a thin white to beige head.  Sweet cocoa, chocolate nibs.  Medium bodied, sweet cocoa, chocolate, roast, light cocoa.  Smooth and toasty, long cocoa.  One dimensional perhaps, but very tasty.  Yeast and more dusty cocoa on the finish.

Bottle.  Pours dark brown/black, the initial fizzle of tan head goes away pretty quickly.  The aroma is almost off-putting theres so many things going on ... an essence of prunes in burnt sugar, coffee, and sweet tropical fruit.  Thankfully, once the tongue gets involved, it has more finesse.  Built with the insane complexity thats made Dogfish famous, this one piles on dark fruits, honey, roasted malt, and even some pineapple. (#4775, 9/9/2012)

750mL bottle.  Poured clear, deep garnet with a creamy beige head.. lovely!  The aroma picked up toasty, slightly salty pecans, figs, and warm dark fruits over spicy fruit meat and a touch of honey.. kind of sweet and definitely interesting.  The flavor found warm licorice, dark fruits, honey, and tart oak & fruity notes with peppery spice around.. fairly tart and assertive through the finish.  Medium-bodied with high carbonation on the palate.. a bit too sharp and warm at times.. still interesting.

Location: 750 ml bottle from jcos, 9/5/12


Aroma: Nose has some nutty components, coffee, chocolate, raisin, and candied sugar

Appearance: Pours a clear deep, dark reddish-purple color, a small head, and no lace

Flavor: Tastes fairly sweet and malty, with a nice complexity of sweet flavors that are similar to the nose

Palate: Medium bodied, has a fairly soft carbonation, a sticky, almost cloying feel, and a lengthy finish

Overall Impression: 
This one is rather complex, and rather interesting, but not completely up my alley.  The unbalanced sweet/maltiness makes it just a little lower for me overall.  I could have used some sort of hop balance, this is a beer after all.
Pours a mahogany brown color with and aroma of cherry, hazelnut, and chocolate.  Cherry and chocolate flavor with hazelnut and coffee to round out the flavor.  Great beer!

Another old rating finally put in.  From a Whole Foods keg.  Poured a deep brown, decent head.  Aroma mostly of cherry accented sweet malts with a hint of chocolate.  Flavor matched.  A faint sour note at the finish of the dubbel.  Not bad, but considering the kitchen sink thrown into this beer, it really didnt hit me as that complex.  As usual from DFH, neat experiment.

750ml bottle from the brewery in Milton, DE. Pours a very deep brown, almost black colored body with a finger-width, dense and creamy, brown head that dissipates slowly and leaves a nice lacing throughout. Aroma is toasted nuts and chocolate up front with a nice cherry note, roast, caramel, brown sugar, light herbal spicing, a few fruity esters, and slight graininess. Flavor is similar. Nutty and toasty up front with a nice chocolate, caramel, brown sugar, and bready note. Some fruity esters and cherry in the middle with a light roast, graininess, earth, and light herbal spice. A bit of a coffee note towards the end before this finishes dry and lightly bitter with a nice, nutty sweetness balanced with some fruity esters, toast, and a light spice. Lengthy aftertaste following a soft, medium body and a somewhat creamy, moderate carbonation. Overall, there is certainly a lot going on here, but it all comes together nicely and stays really well balanced. Huge fan of this one.
Brown ale aroma, coffee, mild spiciness.  Brown sugar, alcohol.  Candi sugar.

Tap at the Royal Tavern, Philly - 26/05/12.
Deep brown colour with a thin tan head.
Roasted aroma, molasses, burnt sugar, Belgian yeast.
Taste follows nose but with more dark fruits, quite sweet, not as roasty tasting and a little pepper and spice.
Medium bodied and carbonation. Not a bad dubbel, could have been better balanced, cant quite put my finger on it!?!
user_location: Hazlemere, the lower Xhitlerns, Buckinghamshire, ENGLAND

text:
Draft at Bottles 101. Aroma of roasted malt, dark chocolate, a hint of coffee and maple syrup. Tastes of dark fruit, chocolate malt, vanilla and espresso. This beer rules. Great take on a Belgium Dubbel. Fun to drink and very complex with an inviting aroma to match. A must try.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Dark mahogany with big, foamy, tan head / Complex but muted nose of roast barley, cocoa, coffee, dark fruit, and herb / Medium to full body, soft carbonation, lightly sweet and inky, with good hop balance and mostly dry finish / Complex, somewhat curious and muted flavors of cocoa, hazelnut coffee, cherry, and odd spice / A lot going on, but ultimately I find the flavors kind of flat.  That being said, still got to love Dogfish for trying this sort of stuff.

Pours a deep brown/amber with a somewhat substantial beige head that doesnt disappear quickly. Nose is an earthy, roasted grain with a hint of floral and nuttiness underneath. Tastes nutty, semi-bitter but notably not hoppy bitter. Chocolate, black tea, mild hazelnut and a bit of dark fruitiness all come through as well. Body is slightly heavier than a typical brown ale, imparting some malty sweetness. Definitely a well balanced beer. Its an easy drinker considering the relatively high ABV, but has so much going on you want to sip and savor. Overall, Id say this is one of Dogfish Heads successful experiments.

Pours a reddish brown color with a foamy canvas head. Notes of peanut brittle, brown sugar, milk
Chocolate, and green hops.

On tap at Alewife. Dark brown with a medium creamy brown head and nice lacing. Aroma of roasted malt, caramel, belgian yeast, chocolate, hazelnut and candy sugar. Taste of roasted malt, dark fruits, caramel and chocolate. Mouthfeel is a bit thin. It taste like a good belgian dubbel. I cant find half of the aroma/flavor listed in the description of the beer.
Spicy notes predominate this brown. Tastes malty with some notes of cinnamon and mild chocolate.

Dark brown pour, clear, tan head quickly dissipates. Sweet aroma, red fruit, berries, a little sweet. Similar layering of berries and chocolate in the taste profile. Sweet but also some coffee. Slightly bitter finish. Overall, this is not a beer i would drink regularly but it is very interesting and well crafted.

On tap @ Pony with James. Dark brown pour. This was not very good. The mouthfeel was somewhat gritty and the palate was watery, while the flavors were mostly earthy resin or cigarette ash. A putrid sort of sweetness comes through on the back end, but not like a fresh fruit or anything - kind of like a skunky sweetness. We may have gotten a bad batch/pour because most people seem to love this. One good quality would probably be the roastiness, but as I mentioned, its kind of to the point of ash/cinders.

Bottle... Pours clear and quite dark with mahogany highlights and a small, creamy, cappuccino head. Good retention. The nose provides notes of rich pistachio-almond-praline, mocha and chocolate crème with a subtle spiciness. Full-bodied and oily with lazy carbonation. The mildly sweet, nutty flavor presents some minerals and traces of herbs. Creamy, mocha finish.

Dear Christ. Where to begin. On draft at pony with Brendan. After sampling some stepped pales and IPAs this is a nice blast to the face. What? What did I ever do to you Sam???? No! No! Not to the face! Noooooahhhhh! Pours a deep brownish amber body with thin brown lacing, no head. Aroma is plain, maybe some sweet malts bleeding through. Mouthfeel is horrendous, I dont want to swallow (thats what she said) but I do anyway. Dear Christ. Let it be over. Please god no.

A dubbel?  I see very little similarity.  Much too roasty to fit what I think of as a dubbel.  That said, there is a really interesting spice profile on top of what is a signature sweetness for DFH beers.  OK I guess, but not a dubbel.

bottle at azwine 5/4/12.

porter color...clear orange brown with an off white head.

smells like a porter smells...choco, nutty, roast, florals, cream  and toast.

it tastes the same but tea is all over it...milk and wood notes added in. it is weird but not bad.

medium bodied and soft. needs about four less ingredients to make sense. 6.5/4/6.5/3/14

Bottle: &nbsp Deep copper in color, moderate sudsy tannish head, spotty lacing. &nbsp Big sweet dark breaded aroma, slightly spicy, some dark pitted fruit and floral like shrubs. &nbsp Seems like lots going on with this one. &nbsp Very bready up front, lots of fig/date/raisin too. &nbsp There seems to be a touch of star anise, perhaps some dark chocolate covered cherries and associated sugary white syrupy bits. &nbsp This is very interesting, very much like a Dubbel but also a little different. &nbsp Backside shows a bit of floral shrubiness, a bit nutty too. &nbsp Lots of flavors, making for an interesting experience. &nbsp Body and mouthfeel are fairly moderate. &nbsp Not a heavy example. &nbsp Very interesting beer, with lots going on. &nbsp Very enjoyable.
Bottle. Clear reddish brown with a creamy off white head. Sweet earthy chocolate and pomegranate aroma. Earthy Tastes of honey pomegranate chocolate and allspice. Nice creamy palate. Very good.

Dark mahogany with a thin white head. The nose shows some caramel, roasted nuts and some fig. Full bodied, sticky, thick palate. Chocolate, coffee and more pit fruit. Way too sweet to be construed as a Dubbel.

Bottle from Beer Revolution. Pours dark brown with an indescribable aroma, maybe rotten bananas. There is a very strange banana bread flavor wtih a some smoked malt and a very grainy feel. Wouldnt want to drink a whole 750 of this, but its quite interesting.

Aromas of coffee,molasses, bread. murky dark brown with negligible head. Dances nicely through the mouth .Appreciate the lack of roast malt, maybe its more  porter than a stout,, coffee, blue berry, rye, brown sugar. on tap at OBF buzz tent.
Pours a dark amber color.  Aroma  has soe sugary fruit flavors and perhaps a little chocolate.  Taste is sweet and floral with some chocolate in there as well.  An interesting and good beer.

750, capped. Pours a murky dark brown with a dense and creamy tan head. Very toasty roasty nose, seriously smells like sweet brown bread baking. Creamy medium body with soft carb. Toast, nuts, brown bread, and some biscuit on the mid palate. Mild biscuity finish. Not too bad.

Bottle.  Aroma: dark fruit, toasty malt, a touch of molasses, light sweetness, hints of coffee and chocolate.  Pours slightly hazy, brown in color with an off-white head, decent retention and lacing.  Very malt-focused flavor: lots of toast/biscuit, with molasses, roast malts, coffee, and chocolate woven in.  Slight spiciness, pepper and herbs, low-medium bitterness.  Medium body, carbonation is medium-high.  Nice brew.

Bottle. Moderate to heavy malt aromas of dark bread, hay, cereal, roasted, milk chocolate and mild coffee, Light herbs and faint dough for the hops and yeast, with a note of brown sugar. Head is average to large in size, fizzy, light tan with some slippery lacing and is mostly diminishing. Color is clear mahogany. Flavor starts lightly to moderately sweet and moderately acidic, then finishes lightly acidic and bitter. Palate is medium, slick with a soft to lively carbonation. A malt dominant beer and good balance with the adjuncts, this Specialty Grain Beer is easy to drink and has a nice palate.

Eyed this just chillin .. . pours a deep amber .. medium head, great brussels .. . the spices are subtle and well balanced, just wanted a bit more of the rooibos .. . much better than Pangea .. . . Id hate to be a dragon, Id get so angry trying to blow out my birthday candles.

Bottle from GCM Liquor.  Pours a dark caramel color with a trim light tan head.  Aroma of chocolate, hazelnut, candied sugar and some herbiness.  Taste is semi-sweet with some esters and semi-sweet dark chocolate.  Some florals.  Pretty nice beer.  Unique.

UPDATED: APR 5, 2013 
Draught @ City Beer Store and Tasting Room
Aroma is sweet with roasted malt, vanilla and some brown sugar. Flavour is malty with sugar. Roasted finish with coffee and licorice. Malty palate A bit unusual and too sweet dubbel. Interesting and good anyway.

Draught @ City beer, San Francisco.
Pours murky dark brown, almost black color with minimal head. Aroma of liquorice, dark ripe fruits, spices and dark malts, a bit of yeast also. Flavour of dark ripe fruits, liquorice, dark malts and yeast. Very complex and tasty.
4336

On tap. Darkest dubbel Ive seen. Mahogany pour, fizzy tan head. Aroma is vanilla, molasses, dried prune, a little pepper. Medium and slick. Sweet dried fruit up front with a slightly sour finish. Really unique dubbel.

Sampled on 5/5/2012. This specialty grain ale pours a medium dark brown color from the tap. Small sized white foamy head. The aroma is dark fruit, chocolate, roasty, and spicy. A medium bodied specialty beer. The malts are fruity, chocolate and roasty. The hops are herbal and earthy. A complex beer, there are a lot of flavors going on here. Candi sugar, chocolate, some honey, dark fruits and a whole bunch of spices that I cant really identify. Interesting beer, the complex flavors do not seem to clash as much as one would expect. Mouthfeel is full. Finish is clean and smooth. Aftertaste is a touch dry and sweet.

Malty aroma has fruity and caramel notes and a hint of cloves. It pours a semi-transparent dark cinnamon brown with a respectable light tan head. Flavor has a nice mix of malt, fruit, cloves, cinnamon and yeast. Smooth texture has firm body, if not a whole lot of fizz. From the name I get the impression that this is the successor to Pangaea. Whatever, its one tasty beer!

Tap. Pours clear deep brown with a small beige head and minimal lacing. Aroma is chocolate, roasted malt, spice, floral, and molasses. Flavor is molasses, roasted malt and spices. Extremely complex brew with a rich and creamy palate feel.

Pours a deep and dark brown color with a thick off white head.  Aroma is of roasty chocolate malt goodness.  Flavor is loaded with sweeter chocolate malts, barley, big roastiness, and molasses.  Leaves a roasty toasty malt finish.  Full bodied brew here.  Its nice to see Dogfish Head make a winner like this.

What to say about this? This is an all around good beer with a lot of things going on. Not too heavy or light, but all the different ingredients seem to get muddled up and make them hard to identify. A decent beer, but quite pricey.

750 ml bottle. Pours dark brown but looks ruby red in the light; has a large beige head that collapses into a blanket of foam after a few minutes. Aroma is malt-driven--smells like chocolate-covered cherries; I smell sweetness, it might be the honey; floral notes are prominent. Taste is sweet and meaty, delicious. Honey and floral flavors are strong, and again, that chocolate covered cordial cherry flavor. This is a well-crafted delicious brew. From the aroma, I thought it might be cloyingly sweet and not to my liking, but Im glad I was wrong.

Pours a deep, dark ruby red with a thin pillowy head that dissipates rather quickly.  Aroma of kola nuts (Coca-Cola), stone fruit (dried cherry) , and brandy.  Taste is sweet, dominated by toasted caramel and chocolate malts.  A boozy flavor of cherry is also noticeable, with just a hint of grassiness on the end.  Mouthfeel is watery, with a prickle of light carbonation.  In sum, a beer that is faithful to the style, but I am unable to taste or recognize most of the "special" ingredients.  Not quite as eclectic tasting as many of DFHs "experimental" beers, but worth a try if you like dubbel ales.

From the bomber bottle, pours a deep dark amber with a thick off white foamy head.  Beer aroma - amber malts mostly, a little bit of dark fruit.  Full taste, a little smokey, amber malts, hint of alcohol, dark fruits, a little sweetness, thin and quaffable, chocolate notes as it warms.  Excellent beer on tap, had to buy the bottle to rate.

Pours brown with a nice dense head.  Nice aroma of nuts, chocolate, yeast, coffee, caramel.  Smooth palate with tastes of chocolate, caramel, coffee, peaches?, bread.  Nice and interesting.  Has some unusual flavors, but is well put together.
Pours a really dark brown with a very small head. I dont get much aroma off this one, but it has a very smooth taste. So smooth that no specific flavor really pops, but they all blend well.

Bottle. Pours with an extremely deep brown, near black hued body with a massive tan head composed of very fine grain bubbles. Aromas are strongly of isoamyl acetate, nutty, alcohol, maple, molasses, tea, soil and sesame. Lightly tangy and floral, tea, ceylon cinnamon. Very fragrant. and a touch vegital. Some freshly baked rye bread. Flavors are nutty, malty, warm. Fresh baked bread, coffee, tea, floral, earthy, and lightly smokey. Very intense. Nutty, herbal, with a mellow bitterness, strong tea and light tannin. Lively bubbles, medium dry and lightly warming with some lasting, low intensity tannins.

Bottle: The aroma consists of chocolate, anise, and some spice. It pours a dark brown with some orange highlighted transparency when held to the light. It has a small beige head that leaves behind some decent webbing for lacing. The flavor starts with chocolate and lighter caramel. There?s some anise in the background. The finish has moderate molasses, brown sugar, and some spices. It?s medium bodied with mild carbonation and a somewhat sticky mouthfeel. Overall, the molasses in the finish wears on me.
Big bottle from Charles Street Liquors. Lots of sweetness, slight rosted flavor, thin lasting head.

Bottle from Canals Berlin. Pours out a moderate ruby hued brown color with a small lacing off white head. Aroma is sweet and of raisins, some Twizzler nibs, honey and dried fruits. Taste is fruit, cocoa, spices, toast, earthy herbal notes, leather, some lingering dried cherries, and some odd spice notes in there also, lots going on in here and definitely in a good way.

On tap at Frisco Taphouse and Brewery in Columbia, MD. 

Murky, opaque dark brown with small khaki head and amazing lacing. 

Aroma of Russian pumpernickel bread, dark fruit, dark cherries, molasses. toffee and earthen yeast. 

Taste of bready malt, amaranth, chocolate, cherries, nuts, spice and tea. 

Medium body and high carbonation. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Pours a dark brown with a minimal tan head.  Smells of caramel, bread. chocolate, seeds/nuts, floral.  Taste is bitter, then a little sweet - very herbal and seed-like, hint of honey.

Panama City Beach, Fl - Chans Wine World (brought back by my wife) - 750 ml bottle. Pours a very dark tea-like brown with a bubbly sticky off-white head. Aroma is earthy and green with hints of sassafras and anise seed. Flavor is unique and slightly complex with brief hints of chocolate, some root beer candy, a touch of black tea, some black dirt earthiness, brief fruity flourish reminiscent of cherries and pears. Mouthfeel is smooth. Interesting, to say the least.

Bottle courtesy of Kirk, thank you sir!  Very dark maroon color, thick light brown head with good retention and solid lacing. Aroma of forest berries, chocolate and spice. Taste is berries, licorice, burnt coffee grounds, spice. Licorice finish. Interesting and certainly unique.
Dark dark brown pour with a nice head. Aroma is banana, fruit and floral notes, but not much. Flavor is banana, spices, pepper, roasty, flowery. Like a dark saison.

Pours translucent black with tan head.  Aroma is spicy...maybe anise.  Taste is complex and warm going down.  Anise, cough syrup, candy sugar sweetness, dark syrup, dark rum, and brown sugar.  Wow.  Very nice.

Bottle. Dark mahogony beer with a tan head. Toffee and earth aroma with light spice. Toffee and caramel flavor with light honey, light earth, and light tea. Medium bodied. Toffee and tea lingers with dark fruit and light spice.

Very complex beer.  Pours a deep red with thick off white head.  Smells of dark fruit and grain.  Tastes very complex.  Lots of chocolate and cereal flavors, some light bitterness, dark fruit, raisins, pepper, some floral flavors, distinct sweetness.  Very clean finish with sweet, slightly spicy aftertaste.  This is one hell of a beer.
This is only uncomplex if you dont know what you are looking for. It is so balanced with all its different elements. Really a great beer to experience. Do it!

Aroma- chocolate, dark fruits, roasted notes, ginger, breadiness
Appearance- dark brown/borderline black, slight white head
Taste- brown sugar dipped dark plums, roasted notes, slight chocolate
Palate- medium-body, medium carbonation, smooth mouthfeel
Overall- Very solid brew from DFH.  Being a fan of Dubbels,  this was a treat for me.  Not very complex but still quite tasty.

Another crazy beer from DFH.  Im not sure that the end result is worth the reaches that this company goes to make this particular beer, but it does end up being a very tasty beverage.  Had on tap at Lansdale Beer Fest, and to be honest my day was getting a bit hazy at this point.

Bomber pours a heavy brownish black with a nice khaki head.  Aromas of malts some carmel and toffee bread  also a touch of yeast molasses brown sugar and hop resin.   Flavor is sweet with some earthy notes.  Body is full and finish is a little boozy.
750 from Whole Foods. Sweet. Raisin. Honey. Malt. Dried fruit. Some interesting spices. A Dubbel for sure. But nicely done.

2012.06.22 - 750ml bottle in snifter.  Pours a deep brown.  Aroma is interesting.  Taste definitely starts off as a Dubbel, similar to Ovila Dubbel perhaps but not as sweet.   This gives way to an interesting blend of spices and flavors.  Nice beer.

This poured a medium to light brown color with a beige head.  Aroma was slighlt burnt sugar some light chocolate and dark fruits.  Flavor was watery chocolate milk, some dark fruit not much else. Kind of muddled and confused beer.

750ml bottle.  Clear dark chestnut pour with a small light tan head.  Sweet malts, light molasses, toasted sesame seeds (wattle seed?), earthy, light chocolate, and herbal notes.  Medium mouthfeel, a little too bubbly.  So far this the best strange ingredient dfh beer I have had.  But its still too expensive.  Interesting for sure.

750 ml bottle thanks to Pineypower, thanks Dean. Poured a deep dark chocolate brown body with a smaller to average sized foamy beige head. Aroma starts off with normal Belgian yeast, slight chocolate, brown bread and then some warmth reveals this odd toasted note (assuming its the toasted Amaranth), slight honey sweetness and green pepper. Full bodied with strong carbonation and an almost grainy finish that slides into sweetness on the very end. Flavor is even more complex than the aroma. Notes of chocolate, pepper, honey, Belgian yeast, brown bread, toasty (once again Im assuming its the Amaranth), earthy, candi sugar and veggies. Interesting and solid.

Draft at Eulogy. Dark brown with a thick foamy head that popped down to a thin ring quite quickly. First impression is watered down coffee. Some honey. Dark malt flavors, but not much fruit. Slight spicy dark carmel. Not awful, but reads so thin that the interesting elements seem lost in a deep blue sea. Interesting, but cannot quite recommend.

75cl, as Urkontinent, new exclusive American brew Anno 2011, thx to Secret Santa!, complex brew, malty/sweet and slightly spicy/roasted, not too heavy, balanced, clear, small head, good and original brew, yet expensive!

750 ml. bottle, 2012- Pours a very dark ruby almost dark cherry color with a thick two finger light tan head, really nice looking beer. The aroma is Belgian sugar, cinnamon, cherries, honey, sweet without being too sweet. The taste is the same as the aroma, only much more complex, chocolate is also in there, I love this beer. Body is medium, carbonation is medium high, finish is dry and lingers. Most Belgian Dubbels dont taste this good, all the flavors just meld together wonderfully, and there is no age on this beer. The best Dubbel and Dogfish beer I have had in a long time.

Aroma of coffee, cream, chocolate, cherries, belgian sugars and some toffee malt notes. Appearance is a nice dark brown with a slight tan head. Taste is earthy, sweet, kind of herbal, hints of cordial cherries, lots of caramel and toffee malts. Nice brew again from DFH

UPDATED: JUL 4, 2012 750 ml bottle poured into pint glass.  Dark brown pour with a white thin head. Aroma of a stout, hint of nutella but tastes like a dubble.  Well balanced flavor from sip to Finnish, amaranth leaves an almost wood flavor earthiness.

Got this beer in the mail as a 750 mil bottle.  Poured into a signature dogfish snifter.  Poured very dark with tan head.  The aroma was earthy malts and hazelnut.  The taste was absolutley out of this world.  This is the best dubbel I have had.  I want more now!  Do yourself a favor and get your hands on this ASAP.

Sampled on draft at 3R6P this beer poured a very dark brown color with a small foamy beige head that lingered and left good lacing. The aroma was roasty malts, cola, cherry and wood. The flavor was malty and a bit toasty and woody with dry tobacco, faint cherry, raisin and cocoa. Long dry malty, woody and cherry finish. Medium body. Interesting.

I believe this is, hands down, the best abbey dubbel Ive ever tasted!  URKontinent is outstandingly delicious.  The beer pours a dark brown color with a substantial tan head.  The head leaves a beautiful, cascading lace around the sides of the glass.  The nose is so inviting and enjoyable, with notes of coffee, chocolate, nuts, earth, toasted bread and light, but spicy, hops.  The body is extremely drinkable, maybe a little drinkable given the alcohol content.  Speaking of which, the alcohol is minimally noticeable, making this both an easily drinkable and extremely dangerous beer!  The flavors are really intense, with more notes of coffee, chocolate, a hint of cream, rustic and earthy malts and light bread.  There is a subtle balance in sweetness with a hint of honey and a spicy dash of dry hops.  The finish is very malty and a little on the sweet side, but leaves you wanting another sip.  URKontinent is a very delicious, very awesome dubbel!
Bottle pours a clear dark red/brown with a thick tan head. Scent is sweet malts, nuts and yeast. Taste is sweet malts, toasty, and nuts. Kinda like a celebrator/porter? Tasty

This was such a cool concept for a beer!  Leave it to DFH to keep pushing the envelope.  Unfortunately, the actual beverage really didnt overly wow me.  Sure, it poured a very pretty clear brown with chestnut highlights and fair tan head.  And the sweet aromatics and flavors of roast, chocolate, toffee, hazelnut and light plum were very drinkable and blended into a decent dubbel. Overall, it was just really sweet and easy to drink.  But there just wasnt any wow factor in the actual way it drank.  As i find with many of the DFH brews the wow factor comes more from the concept of the beer, rather than the actual beer itself.

Pours a deep cherry brown with garnet highlights. A two  finger light brown head  that slowly dissipates into a solid persistent lace leaving a nice trail down the glass.

A ton going on here!  Dark chocolate, roasted malts, toasted brown sugar, caramel , cherry and earthy notes are there as well. The smell is fantastic!

Taste follows the nose fairly closely.  Moderate fruity esters. Starts with plenty of tart cherry and roasted chocolate, with notes of coffee, dates, bananas, and hints of bourbon. The roasted malt is quite pleasant, giving this a toasty, creamy flavor. A pleasant sweetness from either honey or malts. Finishes with the slightest bit of tang.  Very complex. Im not familiar with many of the exotic ingredients so it is difficult to comment on their roles in the flavor profile. All I know is the result ends up being balanced and delicious.

Full bodied, medium carbonation, lush. Alcohol is well hidden behind sweetness. Very drinkable considering the style.

Wow! I am a big fan of Belgians and Im pretty unforgiving of bad interpretations of the style. URKontinent is pushing the envelope with the use of its exotic ingredients but ends up with a bulls-eye for the style.

Draft.  Large beige head, black body.  Aroma is moderately sweet, raisin, candi sugar, light orange, caramel.  Taste is moderately sweet, orange, some raisin, spice.  Medium body, soft/low carbonation.

On tap at Urban Family. I feared this one would be all novelty, but this is a complex, yet quite drinkable brew -- one of the more interesting ones Ive had from DFH in a while. The first thing that comes to mind is a Latin American dessert -- cinnamon and chocolate, with some other baking spices in there as well. Cherry wasnt more than a background flavor -- this was mostly roasted malts, toffee, chocolate and coffee. Fairly thin -- this certainly isnt a palate bomb, and remains quite drinkable through a glass. Nice!

Poured a dark brown with mahogany small tan head. When cap was popped got a nice chocolate covered cherries coming out of the bottle, in the glass coffee, malts and honey, the chocolate cover cherries diminished, has it warmed some floral and sour notes. flavor chocolate, nutty, malt, alcohol, honey. lift a nice honey flavor on the old taste buds.

Has some nice cherry scents with an earthy character as well. Pours a dark brownish red color. Taste has an earthy/nutty flavor with cherries and a very subtle sourness in the after taste.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

bottle.  pours a clear brown with ruby highlights under a thin, filmy, beige head.  i get a lot of fudge in the nose with some licorice-like spice note and lesser notes of chocolate covered dark fruits.  flavor is nutty with chocolate and fudge.  i suppose its the toasted amaranth that imparts that awesome nutty flavor that im really digging.  this is great!
Bottle. I was surprised on how good this was. A nice blend of chocolate, nut, floral and bread. A solid spicy /sweet finish with some hint of fruit.

The aroma is chocolate, nuts, toasted malt, honey.  The appearance is deep red/brown, translucent, off-white head.  The flavor is chocolate, nuts, toasted malt, molasses.  The finish is nutty, spicy, pine hops.  Medium in body.  Interesting and enjoyable.

New DFH 750mL bottle.  Vintage 2012.  Dark brown color. Khaki, light tan foam.  Sweet herbal aroma, nose of heather,  spice, alcohol filled chocolates, chocolate covered cherries.  Soft roasty flavors, some cola, coffee roast character, hints of chocolate essence , floral herb layer as it warms.  Very complex, lots of layers (not in an ogre kinda way (well a good ogre)).  By far, the best of the "off-centered" ingredient DFH brews so far!!  Well done.  Overall, herbal hodge-podge blended with an Abbey Dubbel.  

(3357)

750ml bottle from Liquor Loft.  Brown pour with a small light tan head that leaves a ring.  Aroma is dark fruit, sugar, honey, earthy, nuts, chocolate.  Tastes are yeast, spice, banana, chocolate, floral, grain, brown sugar.  Toasty vibe.  Good balance.  Not bad.

(bottle) A reddish-brown body with ruby highlights and a thin tan head. Heavily sweet aroma, fairly noticeable alcohol, dark fruit (raisin, cherry), chocolate. Medium body, soft carbonation, smooth texture. Sweet dark malty flavor, cherry, nutty, prunes; light grape and chocolate notes. Overall malty and fruity.

Draft at pinnochios. Pours nearly black with a finger of white head. Aroma is very sweet and had a ton of honey in the nose. Taste is very sweet and does have red tea present. Palate is very smooth and the finish is alcohol free. Nice.

(bottle - 750 ml) Deep ruby red pour with a thin tan head. Amazingly complex aroma. Fruit, nuts, hops, chocolate, caramel, toffee... and so many more that I couldnt pin down at the start. Fruity at the start of the flavor with a lot of dry malts and then even more fruit sweetness and a light touch of yeast spice at the end. I kind of liked it in an odd sort of way.
UPDATED: JAN 1, 2014 Tap at Pinocchios in Media, PA. Amber pour with a white creamy head. Nut, chocolate, dark fruit, yeast, and some sweetness here. Quite good.

On tap @ Urban Family. Pours deep black with no head really. Aroma is yeasty chocolate malt. Tart Belgian yeast flavor, thin dark chocolate and green tea-like finish. Way more interesting than your average dubbel, but not worth the crazy Dogfish premium.

Black with a thin tan head. Med body. Fruity aroma. Sweet plummy. But nutty. Sweet yeasty finish. Creative

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Dark reddish in color.... Flavor is roasted malts, coffee and black licorice.... Interesting beer, was hoping for more, but still pretty good.

Bottle via SL.. Pours a murkey dark red/black color. Not what I was expecting. Decent little head, nothing to brag about. Nice aroma. Reminds me of chicory stout. I dont know WTF myrica, amaranth and some other ingrediants taste like but its a pretty smooth abbey dubbel. Kind of coffee, roasted malts taste. Big malt backbone.... I cant pick up any hops but its well balanced. Taste like a stout, but has a body of a dubbel. Very easy to drink for an 8 percenter....

5/31/12. 750mL bottle. Good ratings. This better be good, DFH, because Im tired of your shit when it comes to these special release beers. Brown/amber/red pour with a nice creamy khaki head that sticks and laces decently. A nice combination of aromas that includes chocolate, grainy malts, fruity, yeast, and candy sugar. A better flavor that shows plenty of chocolate and nuttiness with undertones of grain and a bit of a green astringent aspect. Theres also a touch of light fruitiness, Belgian yeast, candy sugar, and a hint of coffee. Not bad, DFH.
Bottle.  Pours brown with a tan head.  Aroma of Belgian yeast, dark fruit, chocolate.  Nice flavor, sweet, and very nicely done.

Bottle - 750mL crowned. Dark mahogany pour with a tall, fizzy tan head thats reduced to a short ring of foam within minutes. Aroma is dark fruit notes, soft chocolate , cocoa, toasted malt, and dusty yeast. Taste is chocolate covered fruit, dark fruit notes, powdery cocoa, dusty yeast, roasted malt, and light coffee notes. Body is medium with a full, bubbly carbonation. Finishes with more chocolate notes, sweet malt, cocoa, dark fruit and soft, dusty yeast. Nice!

A - Pours a dark mahogany-ruby color with a finger of frothy off-white head. The head fades down fairly slowly leaving behind some nice lace.

S - Aroma is a mix of sweet dark fruits, honey, coffee, chocolate, pine, herbs, spices, and Belgian yeast.

T - Starts off with a mix of sweet raisin and dark fruit with some Belgian yeast and spices with a touch of honey. Through the middle, some chocolate and coffee comes through alongside some pine and herbs. The finish is a mix of dark fruit, Belgian yeasts, earthy spices and herbs, and a bit of honey.

M - Medium-full bodied with moderate carbonation. Feels smooth with a sweet lightly spicy finish.

D - Very drinkable. Lots of different flavors and ingredients, but the end result comes together really nicely.

Drank most of a 750ml bottle. Poured a slightly cloudy brown color with a nice off-white head. Aroma is various strange ingredients, a touch of nutty notes, with a bit of yeast. Flavor brought out a bit of chocolate, a touch of nutty malts, yeast, and a touch of dried fruits. Interesting.

Capped 750 from Beverages 4 Less in Santee, CA. Freds the beer guy. Pours dark brown with a foamy/creamy/bubbly beige head. Aroma is floral and chocolate. Near full bodied. Flavor is chocolate and cherry. Clearly. Weird. Some dark malt, but for me this is chocolate and cherry. Lots of other things going on, but c&c dominates. It has dark malt, and the finish is less than dry, but it is quite delicious. DHB may have gone so complex that the flavors are indecipherable. But the taste is good.

Poured into a snifter.

3.0 A: Black color. Three fingers of tan frothy/creamy head. Retention is a bit below average and no lacing is left.

4.5 S: This has a great nose. Through and through this is a solid dubbel first. Lots of caramel, dark fruits, and light peppery spiciness. Fruits include plum, date, raisin, currants, and tobacco. The honey is mild, but there. After that, theres some stuff that I cant really indentify (since I dont know what half the ingredients taste like), but it all works seemlessly into the brew. I can identify the rooibos, which in more complementary than I ever would have expected. 

4.0 T: In the taste, the adjuncts hold a much larger presence. While the result is very tasty, the dubbel gets pushed aside, which is sad since it smells quite nice. Anyway, lots of caramel again with all the fruits mentioned in the smell. Rooibos does great things again (Im going to have to brew with this sometime) while the collective other ingredients give an herbal, somewhat nutty, earthiness. Mild pepper again from the yeast. Definitely unique, which DFH does so well, but also extremely well integrated. Im impressed.

3.5 M: Lighter medium body. This doesnt have the archaetypical Belgian mouthfeel. The carbonation isnt much spritzy at all. Rather, its more of a mellow carbonation that doesnt poke or prod the tongue. Its like the tea is controlling this. Still, decent enough.

4.0 D: Tasty beer, but at $12 a pop, its hard to justify another purchase. This is a once a year type beer for me. I highly recommend giving it a go though.

Serving type: bottle

Reviewed on: 05-19-2012 01:40:29

Fig and almond aroma. Clear brown, medium tan head. Roasted malt, almost smoky withfigs and plums Amaretto at midpalate and beyond. Fizzy mouthfeel and a little warm. Nice take on the style, not too weird, but certainly good.

Pours a dark brown with a hint of ruby along the edges... Rich aromas of malts, chocolate, earthy notes and a touch of sweet Belgian sugar. This beer is damn good... definitely rides the Dubbel style with rich sweet malts but the different flavor attributes from the numerous ingredients really make this a complex beer.  Great chocolate, plum, black tea flavors and the mouthfeel on this one is perfect.

I really liked this aggressive, supercharged belgianesque dubbel.  Like a brown ale, it has the chocolate and the toasty malt - and like a dubbel, it has red fruit and a generous mouthfeel.  Really good.
Aroma of dirt, herbs and honey.  Slight dark fruits.  Tastes of herbs: thyme, mint and slight honey.  Tasty and unique.

25 may 2012, bottle. Dark brown. Nose is strong black coffee. Thin body and faintly fizzy. Flavor is a lot softer than aroma. Sweet mocha, coffee beans. Slight caramel. Nice all around. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Dark brown pour with ruby highlights.  Aroma of nuts, caramel and dark fruit.  This one isnt all that weird...tastes like a dubbel mixed with brown ale.  Cherries are noticeable, some molasses and nuts.  Pretty good, for once.

Poured into a chalice from a 750ml bottle from 2012.

A: Almost opaque chestnut body with a dense tan head, this beer looks excellent in this glass.

S: The aroma is very complex and inviting. Right away I pick up cocoa and a mild roasted hazelnut coffee aroma that come through the strongest. A very mild cherry comes through with some honey and earthy notes, but overall the Wattleseed takes over the flavor, and Im okay with that because this smells amazing.

T: Wow this is just as good in flavor as it smells. The roasted hazelnut coffee hits first with hints of cocoa, while the honey provides some mid-taste sweetness, and the Belgian yeast finishes the beer with a warming slightly spiciness to it and some cherry flavored medicinal esters. This is phenomenal.

M: Medium to thick with light carbonation, drinks very smooth.

O: This is simply amazing, this beer is very complex and super easy to drink. Its also one of the few "weird" Dogfish Head beers I would buy again and again. Dogfish Head knocked it out of the park with this one.

Pours brown with a tan head.  Smells of molasses, some spice, earthy, some clove hints.  Tastes semi sweet and spicy with a nice earthy finish.  I didn;t expect to like this one, but it is interesting.

750ml Bottle:  Aroma of malt, nuts, cocoa, roasting, Earth, and slight dark ripe fruit.  Poured very deep orange/brown in color with a medium-sized, creamy, dense, tan head that diminished but lasted throughout.  Hazy.  Sparkling.  Flavor is medium sweet.  Tastes of malt, cocoa, roast, Earth, a hint of alcohol, and slight dark ripe fruit.  Medium body.  Chalky, dry texture.  Average carbonation.  Lightly sweet, malt, cocoa, Earth finish is chalky and dry.  8.1%ABV is completely hidden throughout.

Pours a deep brown with ample head. Aroma is spicy maple. Taste is dark and malty with a slightly sour undertone. Also tastes a bit of coffee. Finish is nicely crisp. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

750s from Craft and Capones.  Pours turbid dark brownish black with ruby edges through direct light and 2-fingers of creamy, well-retained off-white head.  Nose is great; a big nutty, cacaoey, with earthy esters, black cherry, hops, honey.  Tastes rich, complex, with notes of earthy malt, big hazelnut, cacao, coffee, black cherry, and a complex finish.  This one finishes even more complex than it starts, and the ingredients meld together amazingly well.  So delicious it is a challenge not to drink it down in 3 or 4 gulps.

Location/Date:Bottle on May 20th, 2012.
Appearance:Pours a dark maroon opaque. 
Aroma: Aroma is fruity, earthy.
Taste: Light bitterness, honey, fruit.
Palate:Medium.
Summary: Interesting take on the style with so many ingredients from all over the world.

pours black with creamy off white head. Sweet grainy aroma, with defined notes of dark fruit. Almost a sugar plum flavor. This is a fantastic beer. Almost hints of a "coffee root" flavor, if that existed. The honey also beautifully shines through

Very interesting brew. It pours dark brown with a very small white head. The aroma has fruit, candy sugar, a hint of smoke. The flavor has those aspects with a bit of bitterness to balance. Lively mouthfeel and a medium body keeps it refreshing. Very nice after taste that lingers. Good one.

I liked this as much as about any Dubbel.  Pours dark purple with minimal head, some chocolate and a lot of dark fruit in the nose and palate.  Body is relatively full and sweet, with some spice on top of the fruit.  Finish is dry, but not overly so, still and little sweet, and satisfying.

Tap.  Pours opaque with a small, fizzy light tan head, short retention with spare lacing.  Aroma is dark chocolate, coffee, roast, and nutty malt, figs, prunes and cherries with light earthy hops.  Flavor is dark and bitter malt, chocolate, prunes, wood and earthy hops with a dry finish.  Full body and medium carbonation.

Bottle.  Pours a medium brown color with an off-white soapy head.  Has a complex aroma.  Chocolate, honey, caramel, roast, candi sugar and perhaps some grape notes.  Sweet creamy roasty chocolate taste with a subtle bitter layer and sugary honey notes through the finish.  Wow.  Not a traditional double but this experiment works.  A really good brew.
Tap @ Mayor Foco. Brown appearance with a brown head. Candy sugar, caramel, somewhat fruity, honey aroma.  Fairly spicy yeasty, caramel, chocolate, dark fruity, honey flavor. Rich flavor but good.

Poured a very cloudy/hazy brown color with a slight red color.  Silky and large off-white head.  Aroma is very earthy with seeds, roots, some sesame, and a touch of honey.
